'''Balance of plant''' ('''BOP''') is a term generally used in the context of [[power engineering]] to refer to all the supporting components and auxiliary systems of a power plant needed to deliver the energy, other than the generating unit itself. These may include [[transformer]]s, [[inverter]]s, supporting structures etc., depending on the type of plant.<ref>{{cite web|first1=Chris|last1=McGee|title=Balance of Plant for Wind Projects|url=http://www.esru.strath.ac.uk/EandE/Web_sites/11-12/Wind_BOP/bop.html|website=www.esru.strath.ac.uk|accessdate=29 June 2016}}</ref><ref name=alstomHydro>{{cite web|title=Balance Of Plant|url=http://alstomenergy.gepower.com/Global/Power/Resources/Documents/Brochures/hydro-balance-of-plant-bop.pdf|publisher=Alstom|accessdate=29 June 2016}}</ref><ref name="NFCRC1">{{cite web|title=NFCRC: FUEL CELL POWER PLANT: MAJOR SYSTEM COMPONENTS - Balance of Plant |url=http://www.nfcrc.uci.edu/3/FUEL_CELL_INFORMATION/FCexplained/FC_Comp_BalanceOfPlant.aspx |website=www.nfcrc.uci.edu |accessdate=29 June 2016 }}{{dead link|date=August 2017|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>
