A '''localized surface plasmon''' (LSP) is the result of the confinement of a [[surface plasmon]] in a [[nanoparticle]] of size comparable to or smaller than the wavelength of light used to excite the [[plasmon]]. The LSP has two important effects: [[electric fields]] near the particle’s surface are greatly enhanced and the particle’s optical absorption has a maximum at the [[plasmon]] [[resonant frequency]]. The enhancement falls off quickly with distance from the surface and, for [[noble metal]] nanoparticles, the resonance occurs at visible wavelengths.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Rycenga | first1 = Matthew | last2 = Cobley | first2 = Claire M. | last3 = Zeng | first3 = Jie | last4 = Li | first4 = Weiyang | last5 = Moran | first5 = Christine H. | last6 = Zhang | first6 = Qiang | last7 = Qin | first7 = Dong | last8 = Xia | first8 = Younan | year = 2011 | title = Controlling the Synthesis and Assembly of Silver Nanostructures for Plasmonic Applications | url = | journal = Chem. Rev. | volume = 111 | issue = 6| pages = 3669–3712 | doi=10.1021/cr100275d| pmid = 21395318 | pmc = 3110991 }}</ref> For semiconductor nanoparticles, the maximum optical absorption is often in the near-infrared and mid-infrared region.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Liu | first1 = Xin | last2 = Swihart | first2 = Mark T. | year = 2014 | title = Heavily-doped colloidal semiconductor and metal oxide nanocrystals: an emerging new class of plasmonic nanomaterials | url = | journal = Chem. Soc. Rev. | volume = 43 | issue = 11| pages = 3908–3920 | doi = 10.1039/c3cs60417a | pmid = 24566528 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Zhou | first1 = Shu | last2 = Pi | first2 = Xiaodong | last3 = Ni | first3 = Zhenyi | last4 = Ding | first4 = Yi | last5 = Jiang | first5 = Yingying | last6 = Jin | first6 = Chuanhong | last7 = Delerue | first7 = Christophe | last8 = Yang | first8 = Deren | last9 = Nozaki | first9 = Tomohiro | year = 2015 | title = Comparative study on the localized surface plasmon resonance of boron- and phosphorus-doped silicon nanocrystals | url = | journal = ACS Nano | volume = 9 | issue = 1| pages = 378–386 | doi = 10.1021/nn505416r | pmid = 25551330 }}</ref>
== Applications == The [[plasmon]] [[resonant frequency]] is highly sensitive to the [[refractive index]] of the environment; a change in [[refractive index]] results in a shift in the [[resonant frequency]]. As the resonant frequency is easy to measure, this allows LSP nanoparticles to be used for [[nanoscale]] sensing applications.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Mayer|first=Kathryn M.|author2=Hafner, Jason H. |title=Localized Surface Plasmon Resonance Sensors|journal=Chemical Reviews|year=2011|volume=Plasmonics|issue=111|pages=3828–3857|doi=10.1021/cr100313v|pmid=21648956}}</ref> Nanostructures exhibiting LSP resonances are used to enhance signals in modern [[analytical technique]]s based on [[spectroscopy]]. Other applications that rely on efficient light to heat generation in the nanoscale are [[heat-assisted magnetic recording]] (HAMR) , [[Photothermal therapy#Gold NanoRods (AuNR)|photothermal cancer therapy]], and thermophotovoltaics. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=ElKabbash|first=Mohamed, et. al.|date=2017|title=Tunable Black Gold: Controlling the Near-Field Coupling of Immobilized Au Nanoparticles Embedded in Mesoporous Silica Capsules|journal=Advanced Optical Materials|volume=5|issue=21|pages=1700617|doi=10.1002/adom.201700617}}</ref> So far, high efficiency applications using plasmonics have not been realized due to the high ohmic losses inside metals especially in the optical spectral range (visible and NIR). <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Khurgin|first=Jacob|date=2015|title=How to deal with the loss in plasmonics and metamaterials|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/nnano.2014.310|journal=Nature Nanotechnology|volume=10|issue=1|pages=2–6|via=|arxiv=1411.6577|bibcode=2015NatNa..10....2K|doi=10.1038/nnano.2014.310|pmid=25559961}}</ref>,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=ElKabbash|first=Mohamed, et. al.|date=2017|title=Ultrafast transient optical loss dynamics in exciton–plasmon nano-assemblies|url=http://pubs.rsc.org/en/content/articlehtml/2017/nr/c7nr01512g|journal=Nanoscale|volume=9|issue=19|pages=6558–6566|via=|doi=10.1039/c7nr01512g|pmid=28470299|hdl=11693/37238}}</ref>
