{{For|the 1924 Harry Carey movie|Roaring Rails}}
{{merge to|Railgrinder|discuss=Talk:Railgrinder#Proposed merge with Roaring rails|date=December 2017}}
{{notability|date=January 2012}}
{{one source|date=January 2012}}

'''Roaring rails''' is a phenomenon of short-wave [[wikt:corrugated|corrugation]] observed in [[railroad track]]s. Despite being a widely observed type of railroad track deformity, the reason it occurs was not known or researched until recently.

==Introduction==
Roaring rails are very short wave corrugations that range from 25 to 75 millimeters in length. It is commonly associated with high speed passenger, transit, and light [[axle load]] railroad operations.

==Causes==
It is generally accepted that a few distinct causes lie behind different wavelengths of railroad corrugation. One study{{Citation needed|date=September 2012}} indicates that the specific short-wave railroad deformity is mainly caused by pinned-pinned resonance, in which the rail vibrates as a fixed beam, as if pinned between periodically placed [[Railroad tie|sleepers]]. The dynamic train-track interaction that causes fixed frequency vibrations at high speeds, commonly observed in light load [[Rapid transit|metro]] operations, and the anti-resonance caused by the pinning of the rails on sleepers, causes deformation and the "roaring" corrugation of the rails.

==References==
{{Refbegin}}
* Stuart Grassie, John Edwards, James Shepherd. July 2007. ''Roaring rails an enigma largely explained'', International Railway Journal
* American Railway Engineering Association. 1998 ''Manual for Railway Engineering'', AREA, Washington DC.
{{Refend}}

