[[Category:Permanent way]]

{{Refimprove|date=December 2009}}
'''Scale focus''', or '''zone focus''', is a type of focusing system used by many inexpensive [[camera]]s from the 1940s and 1950s. These cameras have an adjustable focus, but lack a focusing aid such as a [[rangefinder]]. It is necessary to determine the distance to the subject and set the focus using a scale printed on the lens. To get properly focused photographs with this type of camera requires accurate estimation of the distance to the subject, or measurement by other means, e.g. a [[tape measure]].

== Technique ==
[[File:Lens aperture side.jpg|thumb|Zone focusing fixes a [[depth of field]], which can be read off of the DOF scale on the focus ring, as shown here – DOF is 1 meter to 2 meters, with aperture f/11 and focal plane at 1.4 meters.]]
Today the term "zone focus" refers to the technique of setting a fixed focal distance (turning off [[autofocus]]), and often a fixed aperture, hence fixing the [[depth of field]], and then taking photographs at that distance; the DOF can be read off of the DOF scale on the [[focus ring]], hence the term "zone". This is frequently used in [[street photography]] to allow rapid and candid "shooting from the hip" (shooting without composing in the viewfinder) and avoiding autofocus lag.<ref>[http://www.markushartel.com/blog/learn-from-markus/zone-focusing Zone Focusing], Markus Hartel, January 22, 2006</ref><ref>[http://photo.net/street-documentary-photography-forum/007j4H Zone Focus], photo.net, March 2004</ref>{{Citation needed|date=June 2011}} Zone focusing is also useful for pet action photography, where the time delay of focusing may be unworkable.

== See also ==
* [[Depth of field#Zone focusing|Depth of field: Zone focusing]]

